# Archibald Campbell, 5th Earl of Argyll

Archibald Campbell, 5th [Earl of Argyll](/Earl_of_Argyll) (1532/1537 – 12 September 1573) was a Scottish nobleman, peer, and politician. He was one of the leading figures in the politics of [Scotland](/Scotland) during the reign of [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots), and the early part of that of [James VI](/James_I_of_England). [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)

## Rise to prominence

Succeeding his father [Archibald Campbell, 4th Earl of Argyll](/Archibald_Campbell,_4th_Earl_of_Argyll) in the [earldom](/Earl_of_Argyll) in 1558, Argyll's inheritance made him one of the most powerful magnates in the kingdom. A devout Protestant, he along with his brother‑in‑law, [Lord James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray](/James_Stewart,_1st_Earl_of_Moray), illegitimate son of [James V of Scotland](/James_V_of_Scotland), became an adherent of [John Knox](/John_Knox) about 1556. Like his father he was one of the most influential members of the party of religious reform, signing what was probably the first "godly band" in December 1557, and Argyll soon became one of the leaders of the [Lords of the Congregation](/Lords_of_the_Congregation). [1] Together, Argyll and Stewart negotiated with [Sir William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley](/William_Cecil,_1st_Baron_Burghley) to secure English aid against the regent, [Mary of Guise](/Mary_of_Guise), by the [Treaty of Berwick](/Treaty_of_Berwick_(1560)), [2] and were largely responsible for the negotiation of the [Treaty of Edinburgh](/Treaty_of_Edinburgh) in 1560, which saw the triumph of the Congregation and the withdrawal of French and English troops from Scotland. [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) It was about this time that Cecil referred to Argyll as "a goodly gentleman universally honoured of all Scotland." [1]

## Influences of national events

### Mary's court

With the young queen's return to Scotland in 1561, Argyll and Stewart, now [Earl of Moray](/Earl_of_Moray), retained their leading roles in the kingdom, continuing to pursue an anglophilic policy, and Argyll was separated from the party of Knox. Mary, Queen of Scots, and Moray came to [Castle Campbell](/Castle_Campbell) in January 1563 to celebrate the marriage of his sister, Margaret Campbell, to [James Stewart, 1st Lord Doune](/James_Stewart,_1st_Lord_Doune). Her courtiers put on a [Masque](/Masque), dressed as shepherds. [3]  

Mary and her court wore [Highland clothes](/Highland_dress) for a visit to [Argyll] and [Inveraray](/Inveraray_Castle) in 1563. Mary wore a "marvellous fair" costume which had been a gift from [Agnes Campbell](/Agnes_Campbell) the wife of [James MacConel or MacDonald](/James_MacDonald,_6th_of_Dunnyveg) of [Dunyvaig](/Dunyvaig_Castle). [4]

### Chaseabout raid

The Earl of Argyll was said to be an opponent of the planned [wedding of Mary, Queen of Scots, and Henry, Lord Darnley](/Wedding_of_Mary,_Queen_of_Scots,_and_Henry,_Lord_Darnley). It was said that Argyll was a leader of a plot to kidnap Mary and [Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley](/Henry_Stuart,_Lord_Darnley) in June 1565 as they travelled between Perth and Edinburgh. They would be imprisoned in [Lochleven Castle](/Lochleven_Castle) or Castle Campbell. [5] [6] According to [Adam Blackwood](/Adam_Blackwood_(writer)) the plot failed while the other conspirators were waiting for Argyll, when the Laird of [Dowhill](/Dowhill_Castle) gave Mary a warning. [7] The English diplomat [Thomas Randolph](/Thomas_Randolph_(ambassador)) said that Argyll came towards [Kinross](/Kinross) hoping to meet Mary, but only to join her for a discussion over dinner. [8]

### Mary at Lochleven

Argyll can be connected to the assassinations of [David Rizzio](/David_Rizzio) in 1566 and of [Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley](/Henry_Stuart,_Lord_Darnley) in 1567. Although supposed to be a signatory of the [Ainslie Tavern Bond](/Ainslie_Tavern_Bond), [11] Argyll was horrified by the Queen's marriage to [James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell](/James_Hepburn,_4th_Earl_of_Bothwell). He joined with Moray and other Protestant leaders in fighting Mary and Bothwell in that year, leading to the capture of the queen at [Carberry Hill](/Carberry_Hill), but broke with his former allies over the question of deposing the queen.

### Offices held and military involvement

With Mary's escape from prison in 1568, Argyll became the leader of the Queen's Party, and led Mary's army in the defeat at [Battle of Langide](/Battle_of_Langside) in which he showed little military skill. He continued to champion the queen's cause following her flight to England, but eventually reconciled with the regent [Matthew Stewart, 4th Earl of Lennox](/Matthew_Stewart,_4th_Earl_of_Lennox) in 1571, and lent his support to the King's party, as a means of restoring peace and lessening English meddling in Scottish affairs. He was appointed to the [Privy Council of Scotland](/Privy_Council_of_Scotland) that year, and became [Lord Chancellor of Scotland](/Lord_Chancellor_of_Scotland) in 1572.

### Role in Ulster politics

Argyll, in his role as [Campbell](/Clan_Campbell) clan chief, was also heavily involved in the politics of [Ulster](/Ulster) during the 1560s. Although he initially hoped for an alliance with the English to secure his claims on land possessed by the [O'Donnell](/O%27Donnell) and [Sorley Boy MacDonnell](/Sorley_Boy_MacDonnell) families against the encroachment of the [O'Neill](/O%27Neill_(Irish_chieftain)), English unwillingness to work with him led him to ally with [Shane O'Neill](/Shane_O%27Neill_(Irish_chieftain)), [12] and orchestrate a marriage alliance among the three feuding clans of Ulster, which would ultimately have major effects on Irish history with the eruption of the [Hugh O'Neill](/Hugh_O%27Neill,_Earl_of_Tyrone) rebellion in the 1590s.

In February 1569, an English official, [Nicholas White](/Nicholas_White_(lawyer)), visited Mary, Queen of Scots, at [Tutbury Castle](/Tutbury_Castle). They mentioned that he was going to Ireland, and White said that the chiefest troubles of Ireland proceed from the north of Scotland, through the Earl of Argyll's "supportation". Mary did not give him much of an answer. [13]

## Marriages and death

He first married [Lady Jean Stewart](/Lady_Jean_Stewart) (died 1588), daughter of [James V of Scotland](/James_V_of_Scots) and [Elizabeth Bethune](/Elizabeth_Bethune); he was thus half‑brother‑in‑law to Mary and to Moray. After divorcing Jean Stewart, Argyll married Janet Cunningham, daughter of the [Earl of Glencairn](/Alexander_Cunningham,_5th_Earl_of_Glencairn) in August 1573. Janet Cunningham gave birth to the Earl's stillborn posthumous son in June 1574. [14] She subsequently married Humphrey Colquhoun of Luss and died in 1585. [15]

Argyll died in September 1573, without male issue, and was buried at [Kilmun Parish Church](/Kilmun_Parish_Church_and_Argyll_Mausoleum). He was succeeded by his half‑brother [Colin Campbell](/Colin_Campbell,_6th_Earl_of_Argyll).

